00:25.125 --> 00:27.876
I carry with me the
burden of having seen

00:27.918 --> 00:30.584
man's inhumanity to man in ways

00:30.626 --> 00:33.459
which are incredible
to a rational mind,

00:33.500 --> 00:35.792
and that will always
remain with me.

00:39.542 --> 00:40.876
<i>I am Ben Ferencz.</i>

00:43.209 --> 00:48.000
<i>70 years ago,
I was a prosecutor at the.</i>

00:48.001 --> 00:50.021
<i>Nuremberg Trials,
in what was certainly</i>

00:50.022 --> 00:52.000
<i>the biggest murder
trial in history.</i>

00:53.000 --> 00:56.876
Ben Ferencz is an icon, really

00:56.918 --> 00:59.667
in international
criminal justice.

00:59.709 --> 01:02.751
<i>We're talking about
a</i> man whose career

01:02.792 --> 01:04.667
<i>spans seven decades.</i>

01:06.792 --> 01:08.855
<i>This trial, well what</i>

01:08.856 --> 01:10.918
<i>was most significant about it</i>

01:10.959 --> 01:12.876
<i>was it gave us an insight</i>

01:12.918 --> 01:16.000
<i>into the mentality
of mass murderers.</i>

01:16.042 --> 01:17.751
<i>They had murdered
over a million people,</i>

01:17.792 --> 01:19.501
<i>including hundreds of thousands</i>

01:19.502 --> 01:21.209
<i>of children in cold blood.</i>

01:23.292 --> 01:25.667
Ben is the personification

01:25.668 --> 01:28.042
of the international do-gooder.

01:28.083 --> 01:30.834
Somebody who has no goal in life

01:30.876 --> 01:33.230
<i>other than to bring</i>

01:33.231 --> 01:35.584
<i>justice to an unjust world.</i>

01:35.626 --> 01:39.125
My Dad used to ask
us, and I kid you not,

01:39.167 --> 01:42.417
around the dinner
table every night,

01:42.459 --> 01:45.334
"What have you done
for mankind today?"

01:47.292 --> 01:49.250
<i>War can make murderers</i>

01:49.292 --> 01:51.792
<i>out of otherwise decent people.</i>

01:52.959 --> 01:54.084
<i>That may come as a shock</i>

01:54.085 --> 01:55.209
<i>to some of the viewers</i>

01:55.250 --> 01:56.959
<i>who perceive these mass</i>

01:56.960 --> 01:58.667
<i>murderers as horrible beasts.</i>

01:59.751 --> 02:00.751
<i>Not so.</i>

02:03.250 --> 02:04.751
At such a young age,

02:04.792 --> 02:07.876
in such a critical
moment in modern history

02:07.918 --> 02:09.250
to be in the thick of things,

02:09.292 --> 02:10.709
to do the right thing with

02:10.710 --> 02:12.125
conviction and courage,

02:12.167 --> 02:14.626
<i>and to have witnessed
what he had witnessed</i>

02:14.667 --> 02:15.855
<i>and turned that into a</i>

02:15.856 --> 02:17.042
<i>positive contribution</i>

02:17.083 --> 02:19.000
<i>for a better humanity.</i>

02:19.042 --> 02:20.417
It's really something to

02:20.418 --> 02:21.792
admire and try to emulate.

02:23.918 --> 02:26.292
<i>The impact of
war itself on people</i>

02:26.334 --> 02:28.543
<i>affected me so that I</i>

02:28.544 --> 02:30.751
<i>wanted to stop war-making,</i>

02:31.876 --> 02:33.814
<i>and have in fact devoted most</i>

02:33.815 --> 02:35.751
<i>of my life in that effort</i>

02:35.792 --> 02:38.083
<i>to try and create a
more humane world.</i>

02:40.500 --> 02:42.626
His humanity and his compassion

02:42.667 --> 02:44.938
and his fearless commitment

02:44.939 --> 02:47.209
to justice all of these years

02:47.250 --> 02:48.938
make him one of the most

02:48.939 --> 02:50.626
important figures of our time.

03:32.292 --> 03:35.125
I'm mindful of the
fact that the world

03:35.167 --> 03:37.043
has always been torn apart

03:37.044 --> 03:38.918
by the type of horror

03:38.959 --> 03:41.584
which is featured on TV,

03:41.626 --> 03:44.542
but I'm also always
mindful of the fact

03:44.584 --> 03:46.250
that we are, believe it or not,

03:46.292 --> 03:48.667
making very significant progress

03:48.709 --> 03:49.959
toward creating a more

03:49.960 --> 03:51.209
humane and peaceful world.

03:57.209 --> 04:01.000
Okay,
Ben Ferencz welcome it says.

04:05.125 --> 04:08.500
<i>Ben is someone who
is very driven,</i>

04:08.542 --> 04:10.375
<i>who is extremely passionate,</i>

04:10.417 --> 04:13.042
<i>and has an absolutely
unshakeable belief</i>

04:13.083 --> 04:16.084
in the rule of law and
in international law

04:16.084 --> 04:17.750
that's what drives him.

04:17.791 --> 04:22.209
He is somebody who
thrives on this passion

04:22.250 --> 04:24.792
and thrives on the effort to

04:24.834 --> 04:26.209
try to move things forward

04:26.210 --> 04:27.584
that seem impossible.

04:29.042 --> 04:32.751
<i>When I was a boy or a student,</i>

04:32.792 --> 04:35.042
<i>there was no such
thing as human rights.</i>

04:35.083 --> 04:36.375
<i>There was no such thing</i>

04:36.376 --> 04:37.667
<i>as international courts.</i>

04:38.918 --> 04:40.397
<i>No one heard of the word</i>

04:40.398 --> 04:41.876
<i>genocide for one thing,</i>

04:41.918 --> 04:43.314
and I was the first I

04:43.315 --> 04:44.709
believe to use that word

04:44.751 --> 04:47.000
in the opening paragraph
of an indictment

04:47.042 --> 04:49.042
- where I was the chief.
- Prosecutor at Nuremberg.

04:50.667 --> 04:52.584
<i>Benjamin Ferencz is the titan</i>

04:52.626 --> 04:57.250
<i>of international
criminal prosecutions.</i>

04:57.292 --> 05:00.792
<i>He really established
an incredible</i>

05:02.167 --> 05:04.376
mandate for international

05:04.377 --> 05:06.584
criminal responsibility

05:06.626 --> 05:09.000
for the commission of crimes

05:09.042 --> 05:12.375
against humanity and war crimes.

05:12.417 --> 05:17.000
He laid out a legal
process that has become

05:17.042 --> 05:19.542
a very important one, taking

05:19.543 --> 05:22.042
us into the 21st Century.

05:24.042 --> 05:25.542
<i>I'd never tried a case.</i>

05:25.584 --> 05:27.626
<i>- I'd never been in a.
- Criminal court in my life.</i>

05:27.667 --> 05:29.334
<i>I was 27 years old.</i>

05:30.709 --> 05:31.980
<i>But I knew at the beginning</i>

05:31.981 --> 05:34.438
<i>that if this trial</i>
is going to have any

05:34.439 --> 05:35.584
significance at all,

05:35.626 --> 05:37.689
it has to set a model of what

05:37.690 --> 05:39.751
you should and shouldn't do.

05:39.792 --> 05:41.541
This is a "Order National."

05:41.542 --> 05:45.751
De La Legion d'Honneur,
Presidente de la.

05:45.752 --> 05:47.542
Republique Francaise...

05:47.584 --> 05:49.334
Names me a "Chevalier"

05:49.335 --> 05:51.083
de la Legion d'Honneur".

05:51.125 --> 05:53.250
That gold medal you
see hanging there

05:53.292 --> 05:55.751
is the Medal of
Freedom which I was

05:55.792 --> 05:57.834
particularly glad to receive

05:57.876 --> 06:00.542
because the previous
recipient of that

06:00.584 --> 06:02.272
had been Nelson Mandela, and

06:02.273 --> 06:03.959
I was a strong admirer of his.

06:07.876 --> 06:10.147
<i>I was told that I'd make a</i>

06:10.148 --> 06:12.417
<i>good lawyer or a good crook,</i>

06:13.542 --> 06:14.876
<i>and I didn't quite understand it</i>

06:14.918 --> 06:17.375
<i>'cause I didn't know
what a lawyer was,</i>

06:17.417 --> 06:18.792
but I knew what the crook was

06:18.834 --> 06:21.334
and I didn't care
for it at any time,

06:21.375 --> 06:23.167
so I think that
may have tilted me

06:23.209 --> 06:24.564
toward wanting to be a

06:24.565 --> 06:25.918
lawyer, whatever that meant.

06:29.959 --> 06:32.209
<i>My sister was born in the</i>

06:32.210 --> 06:34.459
<i>same bed I was later born in.</i>

06:36.000 --> 06:39.542
<i>When she was born,
she was a Hungarian.</i>

06:39.584 --> 06:41.209
<i>When I was born about 18</i>

06:41.210 --> 06:42.834
<i>months later, I was a Romanian.</i>

06:44.792 --> 06:46.042
It doesn't really matter

06:46.043 --> 06:47.292
what you call the country.

06:47.334 --> 06:49.043
What matters is how you treat

06:49.044 --> 06:50.751
the people in the country,

06:50.792 --> 06:53.000
and in both Hungary and Romania,

06:53.042 --> 06:54.751
they persecuted the Jews.

06:54.792 --> 06:56.688
<i>So it was prudent for my parents</i>

06:56.689 --> 06:58.584
<i>to get out if they could.</i>

07:01.834 --> 07:03.897
<i>We traveled third class because</i>

07:03.898 --> 07:05.959
<i>there was no fourth class.</i>

07:06.959 --> 07:09.480
<i>Sleeping on an open deck in</i>

07:09.481 --> 07:12.000
<i>midwinter in 1920 was not easy.</i>

07:14.792 --> 07:17.188
<i>I was crying all the time</i>

07:17.189 --> 07:19.584
<i>because my mother had no milk.</i>

07:19.626 --> 07:21.251
<i>My father was being driven</i>

07:21.252 --> 07:22.876
<i>crazy with this noise.</i>

07:22.918 --> 07:24.083
He couldn't sleep.

07:24.125 --> 07:26.918
He was very tempted
to throw me overboard.

07:26.959 --> 07:28.355
And there's been some

07:28.356 --> 07:30.938
indication that he
would've had he not been

07:30.939 --> 07:32.083
interrupted by my uncle

07:32.125 --> 07:33.709
who was traveling with us.

07:37.626 --> 07:39.105
<i>My father was trained as</i>

07:39.106 --> 07:40.584
<i>an apprentice shoemaker.</i>

07:40.626 --> 07:42.834
<i>He thought when he
gets to New York,</i>

07:42.876 --> 07:44.834
<i>he'll be able to make
boots for the people.</i>

07:44.876 --> 07:46.167
<i>No one told him there were</i>

07:46.209 --> 07:49.500
<i>no cowboys in New
York and no cows.</i>

07:49.542 --> 07:51.751
<i>So he found himself
unemployable,</i>

07:51.792 --> 07:54.042
<i>no money, no friends.</i>

07:56.792 --> 07:58.292
It was a tough life,

07:58.293 --> 07:59.792
but they didn't know it

07:59.834 --> 08:01.272
because where they'd

08:01.273 --> 08:02.709
come from it was tougher,

08:02.751 --> 08:04.959
so it was an improvement
no matter what.

08:08.918 --> 08:12.417
<i>This was an area known
as Hell's Kitchen.</i>

08:12.459 --> 08:14.689
<i>It got that name because it</i>

08:14.690 --> 08:16.918
<i>was a high crime density area.</i>

08:16.959 --> 08:19.626
<i>When I became a criminologist</i>

08:19.627 --> 08:22.417
<i>I found that out by
seeing maps of where</i>

08:19.667 --> 08:23.792
<i>the most crime was in
parts of the world.</i>

08:23.834 --> 08:24.918
<i>It was right at home.</i>

08:26.292 --> 08:28.438
It was a tough neighborhood,

08:28.439 --> 08:30.584
Irish and Italian.

08:31.751 --> 08:34.292
<i>With a lot of gang
warfare going on,</i>

08:34.333 --> 08:37.626
<i>but it was no guns, no knives.</i>

08:37.667 --> 08:39.375
<i>It was just you know
beating each other up</i>

08:39.417 --> 08:41.708
<i>or playing craps
on the sidewalk.</i>

08:44.918 --> 08:46.751
<i>I didn't speak English at all.</i>

08:46.792 --> 08:50.125
<i>I spoke Yiddish was
the mother tongue.</i>

08:50.167 --> 08:51.917
<i>My father took me to school,</i>

08:51.918 --> 08:53.667
<i>public school to enroll me.</i>

08:53.709 --> 08:54.751
<i>They wouldn't take me</i>

08:54.752 --> 08:55.792
<i>because I was too small,</i>

08:55.834 --> 08:58.022
I couldn't speak English, and

08:58.023 --> 09:00.209
they said come back next year.

09:00.250 --> 09:01.918
Next year they said
the same thing,

09:01.959 --> 09:03.647
so I finally ended up when

09:03.648 --> 09:05.334
my parents were divorced

09:05.375 --> 09:07.918
and I went to live with

09:07.919 --> 09:11.334
an aunt in Brooklyn,
that's where I started

09:07.959 --> 09:11.334
my educational career.

09:14.918 --> 09:17.126
<i>My eighth grade teacher in</i>

09:17.127 --> 09:19.334
<i>public school 80 in the Bronx,</i>

09:19.375 --> 09:22.001
<i>I was then living back
again with my mother</i>

09:22.002 --> 09:23.042
<i>and my stepfather.</i>

09:23.083 --> 09:25.001
<i>She asked me to bring</i>

09:25.002 --> 09:26.918
<i>my father and mother in.</i>

09:26.959 --> 09:28.083
<i>She wanted to talk to them</i>

09:28.125 --> 09:30.626
<i>and we had a little conference.</i>

09:32.834 --> 09:35.063
<i>The teacher explained</i>

09:35.064 --> 09:37.292
<i>that this is a gifted boy,</i>

09:37.334 --> 09:39.292
<i>and he should go to college.</i>

09:39.334 --> 09:41.310
<i>- Well certainly she didn't.
- Know and I didn't know.</i>

09:41.334 --> 09:43.272
What a gifted boy meant,

09:43.273 --> 09:45.209
'cause we never got any gifts

09:45.250 --> 09:46.563
and I didn't know anybody

09:46.564 --> 09:47.876
who ever went to college.

09:47.918 --> 09:52.125
This was beyond our
knowledge range,

09:52.167 --> 09:54.043
and my mother said well

09:54.044 --> 09:57.001
whatever you want to
do, you know she would

09:57.002 --> 09:58.042
accommodate that.

10:02.167 --> 10:03.751
<i>The Townsend Harris High School</i>

10:03.792 --> 10:04.896
<i>which was the only one of</i>

10:04.897 --> 10:06.813
<i>its kind in the
country where if you</i>

10:06.814 --> 10:08.709
<i>graduated from there
you were automatically</i>

10:08.710 --> 10:09.792
<i>admitted to City College.</i>

10:12.959 --> 10:15.000
<i>I never had to study before.</i>

10:15.042 --> 10:16.834
<i>I heard something and I knew it,</i>

10:16.876 --> 10:18.501
<i>and it was just you know it</i>

10:18.502 --> 10:20.125
<i>seemed to be quite automatic,</i>

10:20.167 --> 10:21.522
<i>but when I got to this</i>

10:21.523 --> 10:22.876
<i>advanced high school,</i>

10:22.918 --> 10:25.168
I flunked the two subjects

10:25.169 --> 10:27.417
of French and algebra.

10:27.459 --> 10:32.209
<i>So I found out there
was a movie house</i>

10:32.250 --> 10:33.750
<i>featuring foreign films</i>

10:33.751 --> 10:37.667
<i>right near where we
live and I went there,</i>

10:37.668 --> 10:40.876
<i>and fell in love with
the French actress.</i>

10:40.877 --> 10:42.959
<i>Danielle Darrieux,
and she was being</i>

10:40.918 --> 10:42.959
<i>wooed by Charles Boyer</i>

10:43.918 --> 10:45.334
<i>and I could hear
them and I could</i>

10:45.375 --> 10:47.500
<i>read in English what
they were saying.</i>

10:47.542 --> 10:49.542
<i>That was a wonderful
teaching tool,</i>

10:49.584 --> 10:50.730
<i>except I came out speaking</i>

10:50.731 --> 10:51.876
<i>like Charles Boyer.</i>

10:56.292 --> 10:58.022
And all that, and that

10:58.023 --> 10:59.751
was very good in French.

10:59.792 --> 11:00.959
Spoke like a Frenchman.

11:05.417 --> 11:06.876
<i>City College.</i>

11:06.918 --> 11:07.959
<i>It was known as the poor</i>

11:07.960 --> 11:09.000
<i>man's Harvard actually.</i>

11:09.042 --> 11:10.876
<i>I didn't know that at the time,</i>

11:10.918 --> 11:12.189
<i>but it was a very tough school</i>

11:12.190 --> 11:13.459
<i>for a lot of tough kids,</i>

11:13.500 --> 11:16.000
<i>mostly Jewish kids who couldn't</i>

11:16.001 --> 11:18.500
<i>afford a college education.</i>

11:19.334 --> 11:20.918
It was a very good school.

11:20.959 --> 11:22.793
Taught me there first

11:22.794 --> 11:24.626
of all, I have to study.

11:24.667 --> 11:26.250
Secondly there's a
lot I have to learn

11:26.292 --> 11:27.876
and I think I did.

11:31.751 --> 11:33.500
<i>You had to decide
what you wanted to do</i>

11:33.542 --> 11:35.626
<i>while you were still in college,</i>

11:35.667 --> 11:36.772
<i>and most of my friends were</i>

11:36.773 --> 11:37.876
<i>going into civil service</i>

11:37.918 --> 11:39.918
<i>or something like that.</i>

11:39.959 --> 11:41.834
<i>I wanted to go into
crime prevention</i>

11:41.876 --> 11:44.188
<i>because I'd seen enough crime</i>

11:44.189 --> 11:46.500
<i>and I've seen juvenile crime</i>

11:46.542 --> 11:49.000
<i>so I was focusing on
juvenile delinquency.</i>

11:53.834 --> 11:55.959
<i>I didn't know anything about</i>

11:55.960 --> 11:58.083
<i>college, about law schools</i>

11:58.125 --> 12:01.876
<i>and I inquired "What's
the best school?"</i>

12:01.918 --> 12:03.355
<i>And I heard that Harvard is</i>

12:03.356 --> 12:04.792
<i>the best school, not Brooklyn.</i>

12:05.792 --> 12:07.768
- All right, so I sent a.
- Letter to Harvard applying.

12:07.792 --> 12:11.083
And lo and behold,
I was accepted.

12:12.626 --> 12:16.542
<i>I had done so well on
my criminal law exam</i>

12:16.584 --> 12:17.917
<i>that they gave me a</i>

12:17.918 --> 12:19.250
<i>scholarship based on that.</i>

12:19.292 --> 12:21.209
<i>Otherwise I could
never ever afford to.</i>

12:22.751 --> 12:24.209
<i>I realized that there were</i>

12:24.210 --> 12:25.667
<i>different classes of people</i>

12:25.709 --> 12:27.918
<i>and the students who
got up and said "Sir"</i>

12:27.959 --> 12:29.834
<i>every time they
asked him a question,</i>

12:29.876 --> 12:31.584
which seemed to me very strange,

12:31.626 --> 12:34.397
and who wore loafers and

12:34.398 --> 12:37.167
no socks or argyle socks

12:37.209 --> 12:38.480
and went punting on

12:38.481 --> 12:39.751
the Charles on the weekend.

12:39.792 --> 12:41.250
This was another world,

12:41.292 --> 12:43.332
<i>- and they had fraternities.
- And things like that.</i>

12:44.334 --> 12:46.125
<i>I had a few friends
from City College</i>

12:46.167 --> 12:48.480
<i>who also went to Harvard,</i>

12:48.481 --> 12:50.792
<i>and I palled around with them,</i>

12:50.834 --> 12:52.334
but that was another social

12:52.335 --> 12:53.834
world at Harvard itself.

12:56.167 --> 12:58.542
<i>I found a program
in the government</i>

12:58.584 --> 12:59.976
<i>where if you were
working for a professor</i>

13:00.000 --> 13:01.334
<i>they gave you a stipend.</i>

13:01.375 --> 13:03.876
<i>I had no money,
I had no money at all.</i>

13:03.918 --> 13:05.918
Roscoe Pound I
particularly admired.

13:05.959 --> 13:08.751
He was known for
his jurisprudence.

13:08.792 --> 13:10.209
<i>He was an old man.</i>

13:10.250 --> 13:12.042
<i>He could hardly see,
he had an eye shade</i>

13:12.083 --> 13:14.667
<i>and I wanted to work for him.</i>

13:15.584 --> 13:17.000
He said "No,
I can't accept that."

13:17.042 --> 13:18.376
"It has to go through my

13:18.377 --> 13:19.709
"brain," he said, his brain.

13:19.751 --> 13:21.810
- "I can't get it go through.
- Somebody else's brain."

13:21.834 --> 13:23.626
So he turned me down.

13:23.667 --> 13:25.751
So I went to see
the next professor

13:25.792 --> 13:27.146
that I was interested

13:27.147 --> 13:28.500
in was Sheldon Glueck.

13:28.542 --> 13:30.918
He was the only one
who taught criminology

13:30.959 --> 13:33.101
<i>- and his first question.
- "How much is it gonna cost?"</i>

13:33.125 --> 13:34.459
<i>I said it's free.</i>

13:34.500 --> 13:35.834
<i>He said "I'll take it."</i>

13:36.834 --> 13:39.542
<i>So I became an assistant to him</i>

13:39.584 --> 13:41.834
<i>and when the war had broken out,</i>

13:41.876 --> 13:44.626
<i>he began to study war crimes.</i>

13:44.667 --> 13:46.226
<i>- So his first assignment.
